Using a bottom-up CYK style search:

1.  For every individual symbol of the string we listed all non-terminals that can
    generate it (e.g. t21 → NT13, t67 → NT19, …, t81 → NT12).

2.  Building the table for spans of length 2, 3, 4 … we obtained only the
    following composite non-terminals:

    • length 2 : NT33(4-5), NT29(6-7), NT8(9-10), NT16(13-14), NT29(15-16)  
    • length 3 : NT27(5-7), NT16(13-15)  
    • length 4 : NT7(5-8), NT4(13-16)  
    • length 5 : NT32(12-16)  
    • length 6 : NT16(5-10)  
    • length 7 : NT4(5-11)

3.  The grammar has only two possibilities for the start symbol:

       S → NT26 NT32      or      S → NT1 NT22

   –  The right-hand NT32 can indeed cover the final five tokens
     (12-16), as shown above.

   –  Consequently NT26 would have to cover the first eleven tokens
     (1-11).  The only ways to introduce NT26 are

        NT26 → NT13 NT4 | NT7 NT4 | NT2 NT23 | NT7 NT13 | NT9 NT22

     None of these works for the span 1-11:

       • The only NT4 we can build in that part of the table is over
         5-11, so the left child would have to cover 1-4.  No NT13,
         NT7, NT2, NT9 or NT23 can be derived from the fragment
         1-4, because no composite non-terminals appear for 1-4
         (no entry in the CYK table).

       • No derivation for NT26 spanning 1-11 can be formed by any
         other splits either – every attempted decomposition fails to
         match a rule in the grammar.

   –  The alternative start production S → NT1 NT22 fails even
     earlier: the longest fragment that can be parsed as NT1 is the
     single token at position 8 (t9) or 9 (t42).  Therefore NT1 can
     never cover the initial part of the string, and the remaining
     symbols cannot be parsed as NT22.

Since no derivation for the whole span (1-16) reaches S, the given
string is not generated by this grammar.

No
